b':smiling_face_with_sunglasses: On September 2nd we introduced the new S-Class! Each of its predecessors marked the very forefront of modern technology. Originally introduced in the spring of 1954, the Type 220 was the first Mercedes-Benz six-cylinder model in a self-supporting design and featured a previously unknown level of comfort. Safe driving characteristics were guaranteed by the single-joint swing axle, which the Type 220 introduced to series production automotive engineering. With the arrival of the revised, more powerful Type 220 S (74 kW/100 PS) in 1956, the letter \xe2\x80\x9cS\xe2\x80\x9d made its permanent entry into the nomenclature of the Mercedes-Benz luxury class and underlined the special class status of the \xe2\x80\x9cPonton\xe2\x80\x9d six-cylinder.\n@mercedesbenzmuseum\n#MBclassic #MercedesBenz #ponton #Sclass #mercedesbenzclassic #ClassicCar #Car #Carsofinstagram #InstaCar #DreamCar #MBCar #Classic #daimler #photography #backinthedays'

b'This beautiful Mercedes-Benz 280 SE 3.5 Cabriolet can be found in our #alltimestars showroom in Stuttgart, Germany. In August 1961, a convertible version of the 220 SEb was presented, which was an exact replica of the coup\xc3\xa9-variant except for the absent roof and required body stiffening. This elegant and representative model became the successor of the 128 series convertible, which after October 1960 had been produced no longer. From a technical and stylistic point of view, the new model was derived from the 220 SEb saloon, which was presented in August 1959, and was also assigned to model series 111. In contrast to their predecessors, the coup\xc3\xa9 and convertible variants were planned as a fully-fledged four-seated models. Enjoy this one virtually in a quiet #museummomentofzen. We stay with you! :camera_with_flash: by @ranier_fernandez_photography via @mercedesbenzmuseum\n#MBclassic #W111 #MercedesBenz #mercedesbenzclassic #Museumfromhome #closedbutopen #digitalmuseum #ClassicCar #InstaCar #DreamCar #Classic #daimler #photography #backinthedays #performance #thebestornothing'

b"We want to keep you safe.
Safety and trust are matters of the heart for us at Mercedes-Benz. 
However, the safety systems of our vehicles can't protect our family and friends from the current health situation. To #flattenthecurve, we need to do more. That's why we have decided to put on hold the production and administration in the majority of our European facilities. 
To stay safe, please try to stay at home. 
In the meantime, we will devote our social media channels on Facebook, Instagram and LinkedIn to make #socialdistancing as easy as possible for you as well as to share important information from health institutes and agencies. So stay tuned \xe2\x80\x93 and #flattenthecurve. :camera: @ranier_fernandez_photography for #MBSocialcar"
